==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*awiz'', from Indo-European ''*h₂ou̯i-'' ‘sheep’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[ei]], Old Saxon [[ewwi]] (Dutch [[ooi]]), Old High German [[ouwi]] (German [[Aue]]), Old Norse [[ær]].

''Indo-European cognates:'' Luvian ''hawi-'', Latin [[ovis]], Greek [[ὄϊς]], Old Church Slavonic [[овьца]] (Russian [[овца]]), Old Irish [[ói]], Lithuanian [[avis|avìs]], Tocharian B ''ā(u)w''.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'e:owʊ/

===Noun===
'''ēowu''' ''f''
# a [[ewe]]
#:''Twahund eowena, and twentig rammena'': 200 ewes and 20 rams.  (Genesis 32:14)

